"'''Queer'''" is a song written and produced by [[alternative rock]] band [[Garbage (band)|Garbage]] for the band's [[Garbage (album)|self-titled debut album]]. The song started as a [[Demo (music)|demo]] during sessions between band members [[Butch Vig]], [[Duke Erikson]] and [[Steve Marker]], and had its composition finished after singer [[Shirley Manson]] joined the band. Manson rewrote the sexualized lyrics to be more ambiguous, and rearranged the song into a subdued [[trip-hop]] and [[rock music|rock]] [[Crossover (music)#Crossover as a mix of genres|crossover]] structure.

In 1995, "Queer" was issued as the band's fourth [[single (music)|single]] in the United Kingdom and second internationally. The song quickly became a modern rock success for the fledgling band, with positive reviews from music journalists, and becoming their first top 20 hit in both the [[UK Singles Chart]] and ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s [[Hot Modern Rock Tracks]] chart. It also earned attention with its music video by [[St<U+00E9>phane Sednaoui]], which featured Manson detaining, stripping and shaving a man from a [[first-person perspective]]. The video earned much airplay on [[MTV]] and was nominated for [[MTV Video Music Award <U+2013> Breakthrough Video|Breakthrough Video]] at the [[1996 MTV Video Music Awards]].

==Composition==
"Queer" began as a rough [[Demo (music)|demo]] around January 1994, recorded during informal studio sessions between [[Butch Vig]], [[Duke Erikson]] and [[Steve Marker]] in Marker's home basement [[recording studio]] in [[Madison, Wisconsin]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Malins|first=Steve|title=What's Our Problem?|work=Q|location=Detroit, Michigan|pages=50<U+2013>53|date=1996-09-01}}</ref> The band had been [[jam session|jamming]] using an [[ADAT]] [[Multitrack recording|eight-track]], [[AKAI]] [[Sampler (musical instrument)|samplers]], and a small [[drum kit]].<ref name="BVGearslutz">{{cite web|url=http://www.gearslutz.com/board/q-butch-vig/398209-garbage.html|title=Garbage (Butch Vig Q&A)|publisher=GearSlutz|accessdate=2010-08-26}}</ref> The band had written around five songs that they felt were pretentious and lyrically simple and literal. They did not want Erikson to sing, even though he was a competent singer, because they wanted to avoid sounding like their previous band [[Spooner (band)|Spooner]]. Vig and Marker were uncomfortable with their vocals so tended to bury them deep in the mix or distort them with effects; on "Queer", Vig recorded a "scratch vocal" consisting of him screaming his way through. The recorded work was later discarded, which Vig explained was because the trio discovered that the musical experiments they were attempting "[don't] work when you're trying to write a song and put it in a context that works".<ref name=Rise>{{cite web|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|title=Garbage Rise From The House That Grunge Built|url=http://www.garbage.net/garbage/articles/@rise.htm|publisher=[[Addicted to Noise]]|accessdate=2011-07-20|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/200012081244/http://www.garbage.net/articles/@rise.htm|archivedate=2000-12-08|year=1995}}</ref> Vig's inspiration for "Queer" came from a novel he had read about "about this woman who was hired to go and make this guy's son a 'man'. The kid is missing a few marbles. But then he realizes that the women who came to his room is also fucking his father."<ref name=Novel>{{cite journal|title=Garbage: Nevermind where they bin' where they goin'?|journal=[[Top 40 Music Magazine|Top 40]]|url=http://www.garbage.com/press/articles/199603/top_40/article14-main4.html|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20010212090050/http://www.garbage.com/press/articles/199603/top_40/article14-main4.html|archivedate=2001-02-12|page=3|date=March 1996}}</ref>  

After Marker saw [[Shirley Manson]]'s group [[Angelfish (band)|Angelfish]] on ''[[120 Minutes]]'', the band invited her to Vig and Marker's [[Smart Studios]] to sing on a couple of songs. One of the compositions was "Queer", whose incomplete lyrics forced Manson to [[ad-lib]] in an audition that was described as "dreadful". The singer afterwards returned to Angelfish, which folded shortly later.<ref name="behindthemusic">"''Garbage: [[Behind The Music]]'', [[VH1]], aired March 31, 2002"</ref><ref name=Serendipitous>{{cite journal|last=Borzillo|first=Carrie|title=Garbage's Serendipitous Success; Popularity Falls into Place for Almo Act|date=1996-03-23|journal=Billboard|location=Los Angeles|pages=9, 97|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iQ8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA97&dq=Garbage%20Only%20Happy%20When%20it%20Rains&pg=PA9#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> Manson eventually returned to Smart for a successful second audition, and then begun working on the songs Vig, Marker and Erikson had created. Manson rewrote "Queer" into a [[trip-hop]] arrangement,<ref>{{cite book|last=Simpson|first=Dave|title=Modern Life is Rubbish|publisher=[[Melody Maker]]|location=UK|pages=42<U+2013>43|date=1995-03-18}}</ref> and added ambiguous lyrics that allowed the listener to make up their own mind about what the song was about. She also re-sung the "Queer" vocal in an understated style.<ref name=Rise/> It was then that the band knew that Garbage was going to work.<ref name=Scene/> 

Garbage incorporated a [[sample (music)|sample]] of the [[drumline]] from [[New Zealand]] band [[Single Gun Theory]]'s track "Man of Straw" on "Queer";<ref>{{cite web|title=AOL Garbage Interview|url=http://www.garbage.net/garbage/articles/@aol.htm|publisher=AOL Online|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090413123322/http://www.garbage.net/garbage/articles/@aol.htm|archivedate=2009-04-13|date=1995-08-20|quote=QUEER is several different loops- There is loop from the Single Gun Theory, Clyde Stubblefield - a a great drummer who played with James Brown and lives in Madison,}}</ref> this [[loop (music)|loop]] was [[multitrack recording|layered]] with an additional drum part performed by Madison [[percussionist]] [[Clyde Stubblefield]], who was known for being the most sampled drummer in history for his uncredited part on [[James Brown]]'s "[[Funky Drummer]]".<ref>{{cite book|last=Aaron|first=Charles|title=Disco-techs and the Sex-O-Lette|publisher=[[Spin (magazine){{!}}Spin]]|location=USA|pages=56<U+2013>58, 60, 62, 64, 128<U+2013>129|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=774lMJwGjVcC&lpg=PA27&dq=garbage%20disco%20techs&pg=PA56#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=1997-06-01}}</ref> Vig opted to hire Stubblefield to play on the record rather than sample him as "you don't use a sample when the genius who played the sample lives down the street from you", and the drummer also contribted to album cut "Not My Idea".<ref>{{cite web|title=THE COALITION FOR CLYDE STUBBLEFIELD|url=http://clydestubblefield.chipin.com/clyde-stubblefield|publisher=Chip In|accessdate=2011-07-26}}</ref> [[Bass guitar]] parts were completed by [[Milwaukee]] session bassist Mike Kashou.<ref name=liner/> The band wanted to sample a [[clarinet]] part from a [[Frank Sinatra]] record, but the licensing for the sample would have been prohibitively expensive. Mulling over some options, such as having a session musician [[interpolation|interpolate]] the part themselves still led to having to pay a large royalties. The idea was dropped.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bardin|first=Brantley|title=Beyond the Pail|url=http://www.garbage.net/articles/@beyond.htm|journal=[[Details (magazine)|Details]]|accessdate=2011-07-20|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20010212095553/http://www.garbage.net/articles/@beyond.htm|archivedate=2001-02-12|date=November 1995}}</ref> The band still liked the idea of using a clarinet, and recorded a part by Les Thimming on the final mix.<ref name=liner>{{cite liner notes|title=[[Garbage (album)|Garbage]]|format=booklet|publisherid=AMSSD-80004|publisher=Almo Records|year=1995|page=3|quote=Bass: Mike Kashou; Addditional drums: Clyde Stubblefield; Clarinet: Les Thimmig}}</ref>

Manson later explained, "It's not, as you might think, to do with being [[gay]], but tolerance. My granny has the expression 'Or's queer, except thee and me, and sometimes even thee's queer', that is that you think you are normal and the rest of the world is freaky, but we're all equally to blame".<ref>{{cite book|last=Aston|first=Martin|title=Scary! Cooing! Loving!|publisher=[[Raw (magazine){{!}}Raw]]|location=UK|pages=22<U+2013>25|date=1995-12-20}}</ref> Garbage did not write the song to particularly appeal to the [[gay community]], however Erikson stated: "As [[musician]]s, we're totally open to [the song's gay appeal]. There's been enough exposure to [[Gay_community#Human_and_legal_rights|gay issues]] in the [[mainstream media]] that people are finally ready to deal with it. Even if it's something controversial, people are still beginning to open up".<ref name=Scene>{{cite journal|last=P.|first=J.|title=Queerest of the Queer|journal=Scene|location=USA|pages=81|date=1996-05-01}}</ref> Erikson added: "The song isn't about sex at all, it's about the loss of innocence".<ref name=Scene/>

==Single release==
[[Almo Sounds]] released "Queer" as the band's second single to [[alternative radio]] in the [[United States]] at the end of August 1995, upfront of the August 15th [[North America]]n release date of ''Garbage''. The song debuted at the end of September on the [[Modern Rock Tracks]] chart at number 30.<ref name=moddebut>{{cite book|title=Modern Rock Tracks|date=1995-09-23|publisher=Billboard|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9A0EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA103&dq=Garbage%20Queer&pg=PA99#v=onepage&q&f=false|pages=99}}</ref> The following week, ''Garbage'' debuted on the [[Billboard 200]] at number 193,<ref>{{cite book|title=Billboard 200|date=1995-09-30|publisher=Billboard|pages=105|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Ag4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA95&dq=Garbage%20Queer&pg=PA105#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> having spent the previous four weeks as a rising [[Heatseekers]] title.<ref>{{cite book|title=Billboard's Heatseekers|date=1995-09-30|publisher=Billboard|pages=17|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Ag4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA95&dq=Garbage%20Queer&pg=PA21#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> At the beginning of October, "Queer" debuted at number 62 on the [[Hot 100 Airplay]] chart,<ref>{{cite book|title=Hot 100 Airplay|date=1995-10-07|publisher=Billboard|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Zw4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA112&dq=Garbage%20Queer&pg=PA114#v=onepage&q&f=false|pages=107}}</ref> peaking a week later at number 57.<ref name="billboard19951014hot100a">{{Cite book|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iA4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA83&dq=Garbage%20Queer&pg=PA85#v=onepage&q=Garbage%20Queer&f=false|title=Billboard Hot 100 Airplay|accessdate=2011-02-08|publisher=Billboard|date=1995-10-14|pages=81}}</ref> In mid-November, remixes of "Queer" were sent to clubs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Queer / Garbage|url=http://cocatalog.loc.gov/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?v1=2&ti=1,2&Search_Arg=Garbage%20Queer&Search_Code=FT*&CNT=100&PID=712KLENMU8ga4Oo5WObkqsf7m0f&SEQ=20110727114244&SID=2|publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]]|date=1995-11-11|quote=SR0000232502 1996-11-11 Queer / Garbage. PRO-A-4827 33 1/3 rpm; 12 in; 4 versions; <U+2117> Almo Sounds}}</ref> "Queer" peaked at 12th on the Modern Rock chart in its ninth week,<ref name="billboard19951118mr">{{Cite book|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZA0EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA13&dq=Garbage%20Queer&pg=PA107#v=onepage&q=Garbage%20Queer&f=false|title=Hot Modern Rock Tracks|pages=85|date=1995-11-18|publisher=Billboard}}</ref> but did not earn enough airplay to chart in the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=Serendipitous/> The song eventually finished its run on the Modern Rock chart in December 1995, for a total of 14 weeks.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Modern Rock Tracks|date=1995-12-30|journal=Billboard|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=nQ0EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA95&dq=Garbage%20Queer&pg=PA95#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>

In October 1995, "Queer" was issued as the band's second single in [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. [[Mushroom Records|White]] issued a three-track [[CD single]] and [[cassette single]] [[B-side|backed with]] two newly-recorded tracks, "Girl Don't Come" and "Sleep",<ref name=aucd/> which had been recorded for the UK release of "[[Only Happy When It Rains]]".<ref>{{cite book|last=Sampson|first=Dave|title=It's a Pity About Garbage|publisher=[[Melody Maker]]|location=UK|date=1995-09-30}}</ref> "Queer" peaked at number 55 in Australia, spending twelve weeks on the [[ARIA charts]].<ref name="aussingle">{{cite book|title=Australian Chart Book, 1993-2009|first=David|last=Kent|publisher=Australian Chart Book Pty. Limited|year=2010|ISBN=0-646-52995-1|quote=02 - 05-Nov-95*HP-55*WI-12 - Queer}}</ref> In New Zealand, "Queer" debuted on the [[RIANZ|RIANZ charts]] at number 45 at the start of November, rising to a number 37 peak three weeks later.<ref name="NZchart">{{cite web | url=http://charts.org.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Garbage&titel=Queer&cat=s | title=Garbage - Queer | publisher=Charts.org.nz | accessdate=2011-01-19}}</ref> Across [[Europe]], "Queer" was issued by [[BMG]] in a similarly configured CD single; a three-track release backed with "Girl Don't Come" and "Sleep".<ref name=eucd/> In [[Belgium]]'s [[Wallonia]]-region, "Queer" peaked at number 24 at the end of January 1996.<ref name="belgwa">{{cite web | url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=Garbage&titel=Queer&cat=s | title=GARBAGE - QUEER (CHANSON) | publisher=Ultratop.be | accessdate=2011-01-19}}</ref> "Queer" debuted and peaked at 7th in [[Iceland]] the following month.<ref name=Iceland>{{cite book|url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?issId=196554&pageId=2936627&lang=en&q=Garbage%20Queer|date=1996-02-10|publisher=Dagbla<U+00F0>i<U+00F0> V<U+00ED>sir|pages=38|title=Islenski Listinn|accessdate=2011-07-26}}</ref> In Spain, "Queer" peaked at number 33 on the airplay chart.<ref name=Spain>{{cite book|last=Salaverrie|first=Fernando|title=S<U+00F3>lo <U+00E9>xitos. A<U+00F1>o a a<U+00F1>o. 1959-2002|year=2002|publisher=Foundation Author of the General Society of Authors and Editores (SGAE)|location=Madrid}}</ref> In April 1996, performed "Queer" live on French television show ''[[:fr:Nulle Part Ailleurs|Nulle Part Ailleurs]]'' and headlined a show at the [[<U+00C9>lys<U+00E9>e Montmartre]] in [[Paris]];<ref>{{cite journal|last=Marker|first=Steve|title=Planes, Food Poisoning and Smelly Buses|publisher=[[Addicted to Noise]]|date=1996-05-10|url=http://cafemomo.com/news/9605diary.shtml|accessdate=2011-07-27|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/19991003160711/http://cafemomo.com/news/9605diary.shtml|archivedate=1999-10-03}}</ref> BMG France released a three-track CD single of "Queer" featuring "Trip My Wire" and the [[Rabbit In the Moon]] remix.<ref name=frcd/>

Initially, [[Mushroom Records]] had scheduled "Queer" to be the [[lead single]] for the UK release of  the debut album ''Garbage'', matching the international single release strategy. At last minute, it was decided to release "Only Happy When It Rains" upfront of the album, with "Queer" rescheduled to later in 1995 to coincide with the band's first UK live show.<ref name="recordcollector">{{cite journal|last=Davis|first=Andy|title=Three Men and A Babe; Welcome to Spooner Town; Goodbye Angelfish|year=1997|journal=[[Record Collector]]|location=London|issue=#209}}</ref> "Queer" was quickly picked up by radio, and was [[playlist|B-listed]] by [[BBC Radio One|Radio One]], whose breakfast slot [[Disc jockey|DJ]] [[Chris Evans (presenter)|Chris Evans]] championed it as his "Single of the Week",<ref name=UKrelease/> and playlisted by [[Virgin Radio]].<ref name="BG">{{cite press release|title=Garbage Album Campaign History|url=http://i7.photobucket.com/albums/y296/boylikearose/Garbage%20Memorabilia/2001beautifulgarbagemarketing3.jpg| year=2001| publisher=Mushroom Records (NCM Group)|accessdate=2008-02-03}}</ref> "Queer" reached number 35 on the airplay chart.<ref name="BG"/> Mushroom issued the single on a [[limited edition]] [[7" vinyl]] and a gold and silver [[CD single]] set on November 20, 1995.<ref name=UKrelease>{{cite press release|title=Queer (Garbage Communication Number 2)|url=http://i7.photobucket.com/albums/y296/boylikearose/Garbage%20Memorabilia/1995Queerpressreleasepage1.jpg|publisher=Mushroom Records|year=1995|accessdate=2011-07-27}}</ref> Each CD single was [[b-side|backed with]] a newly recorded track; "Trip My Wire" on the first and a [[cover version]] of [[The Jam]]'s "[[Strange Town|Butterfly Collector]]" on the second.<ref name=UKrelease/> Four remixes of the title track were spread out across the CDs, with one also appearing on the flipside of the vinyl.<ref name="recordcollector"/> Early indications showed that the single had a [[midweeks|midweek]] position of 10,<ref>{{cite book|last=O'Connell|first=Shannon|title=Trash On Delivery|publisher=[[Melody Maker]]|location=UK|date=1995-12-02}}</ref> however at the end of its first week on-sale, "Queer" debuted on the [[UK Singles Chart]] at  number 13.<ref name="UKChartArchive">{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/1995-12-02/|title=TOP 40 OFFICIAL UK SINGLES ARCHIVE (2nd December 1995) |publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=2010-01-17}}</ref> That week, Garbage made a live appearance to perform the single on ''[[Top of The Pops]]'',
<ref>{{Cite episode |title=December 1, 1995 Episode |episodelink= |series=Top of the Pops |serieslink=Top of the Pops |credits= |network=[[BBC One]] |station= |airdate=1995-12-01}}</ref> and performed both "Queer" and "Only Happy When it Rains" on ''[[MTV's Most Wanted]]''.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=November 22, 1995 Episode |episodelink= |series=MTV's Most Wanted|serieslink=MTV's Most Wanted |credits= |network=[[MTV Europe]] |station= |airdate=1995-11-22}}</ref>

===Collector's format===
As the band had received significant attention from the special packaging of their first three releases, "Queer" was also released in this manner.<ref name="recordcollector"/> Mushroom's [[product manager]] had a longer time to design the package than the other singles; this was a result of "Queer" being held back three months so that "Only Happy When It Rains" could launch the album.<ref name=HBM/> Garbage's original suggestion for "Queer" was to create a jade [[velvet]] box, but Mushroom vetoed the idea over the cost.<ref name=HBM>{{cite book|title=Gar-barge Press Conference|publisher=Here Be Monsters|location=London, UK|date=1995-07-25|quote=As told by Butch Vig}}</ref> The label sourced a plastics company to create the case, which was made from [[Injection molding|injection-molded]] [[polystyrene]], similar to the process of manufacturing [[CD and DVD packaging#Jewel case|jewel cases]]. The company charged Mushroom <U+00A3>10,000 to have the mould created. The end product was finished with [[Frosting (decorative arts)|frosted effect]] for the "G" logo, which was stickered, and within placed the vinyl record in a card picture sleeve; this cost Mushroom <U+00A3>2.21 per unit (a loss of 95p for each sale). This special single had only 5,000 copies issued.<ref name="recordcollector"/>

==Critical reception==
Upon both the release of ''Garbage'' and the release of "Queer" as a single, the song received a positive reception from [[music journalists]]. Leo Finlay, in a ''[[Music Week]]'' article highlighting the campaign for the debut album's release wrote, "'Queer' is eerily reminiscent of [[Magazine (band)|Magazine]]'s stranger moments".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Finlay|first=Leo|title=Talent; Garbage|journal=[[Music Week]]|date=1995-09-30}}</ref> A reviewer for ''[[NME]]'' wrote that the single was "an ode to recognising and tolerating those mis-shapen ones among us",<ref>{{cite news|title=Single Reviews; Queer|newspaper=[[New Musical Express]]|location=UK|date=1995-11-11}}</ref> and when reviewing the album, their own Shannon O'Connell wrote, "there is a bit of [[Pat Benatar]] in [this songs] back-alley swagger".<ref>{{cite journal|last=O'Connell|first=Shannon|title=What A Waste!|journal=[[New Musical Express]]|location=UK|date=1995-09-30}}</ref> A reviewer for ''[[Vox (magazine)|VOX]]'' described "Queer" as "[[Voice of the Beehive]] roughing up [[L7 (band)|L7]]",<ref>{{cite journal|title=Album Reviews; Garbage|journal=[[Vox (magazine)|VOX]]|location=UK|date=1995-10-01}}</ref> Jackie Hinden of ''[[Hot Press]]'' wrote that the song was "a slinky [[work-out]] against a restrained [[work-to-rule]] [[Industrial music|industrial]] backing",<ref>{{cite journal|last=Binden|first=Jackie|title=Dump It Up|journal=[[Hot Press]]|location=Ireland|date=1995-09-27}}</ref> and the publication later made it their Single of the Fortnight, describing it as "Almost indecently brilliant. There's an intelligence at work here in the lyrics and in the music which makes "Queer" a unique proposition, and Garbage utterly indispensable".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Single Reviews; Queer|journal=[[Hot Press]]|location=Ireland|edition=Vol 19; No.23|date=1995-11-29}}</ref> A writer for ''[[Melody Maker]]'' wrote that "Queer" was "sleek, cultivated [[perversion]]... sinister and menacing",<ref>{{cite news|title=Singles of The Year; #48 "Queer"|newspaper=[[Melody Maker]]|location=UK|date=1995-12-09}}</ref> while ''[[Raw magazine (rock)|Raw]]''{{'}}s review described it as "brilliant, Seductive and slow-burning",<ref>{{cite journal|title=Single Reviews|journal=[[Raw magazine (rock)|Raw]]|location=UK|date=1995-11-15}}</ref> and the single reviewer for ''NME'' considered that Manson's performance "elevates a sing-song [[shuffle]] into a [[lullaby]] to sexual [[non-conformity]]".<ref>{{cite news|title=Single Reviews|newspaper=[[New Musical Express]]|date=1995-11-18}}</ref>
''[[Kerrang!]]'' rated "Queer" as their Single of the Week, stating "an incredible knee-trembling fuck tune... the dirtiest pop tune you'll hear all year. [You'll be] sucked into dark [[satin]] sexiness and you'll never want to leave. Gorgeously decadent and utterly fabulous";<ref>{{cite journal|title=Singlez; Queer|journal=[[Kerrang!]]|location=UK|date=1995-11-25|quote={{Rating{{!}}5|5}}}}</ref>

==Track listings and formats==
"Queer" was the first Garbage single to include [[remix]]es as a commercial b-side; Mushroom spread four across the UK formats. These were completed by producers [[Adrian Sherwood]], [[Danny Saber]], [[Depeche Mode]]'s [[Martin Gore]] and [[Florida]]-based group [[Rabbit In the Moon]].<ref name=UKrelease/> In 2007, the Heftybag mix by Rabbit in the Moon was [[remastered]] and included on the limited edition of greatest hits collection ''[[Absolute Garbage]]''.<ref name="absolutegarbage">{{cite web|url=http://www.garbage.com/news/news.php?id=118| title=New Best Of Album|publisher=Garbage.com|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090620204305/http://www.garbage.com/news/news.php?uid=336|archivedate=2009-06-20|accessdate=2011-07-22}}</ref>

