==Music video==
[[File:Garbage-Queervideo.JPG|thumb|left|Garbage attacking the detained protagonist of the "Queer" video.]]

The [[music video]] for "Queer" directed by [[St<U+00E9>phane Sednaoui]] for [[Propaganda Films]] and was filmed in July 1995 in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=queervideo/> Sedanoui's video concept developed from his own personal experience of being "shredded into pieces" by a beautiful woman. Garbage loved his [[storyboard]] for "Queer", feeling it matched the ambiguous nature of the song.<ref name="Sednaoui"/> Manson had chosen Sednaoui as director after she saw the "[[Big Time Sensuality]]" music video he directed for [[Bj<U+00F6>rk]], and later said that Sednaoui "doesn't just take an idea an apply it to different artists, he seems to be able to figure out where the artist is coming from and make the photographs and the videos unique to that group."<ref name="Sednaoui">{{cite video|title=Stephane Sednaoui & Shirley Manson: Filming 'Queer' | people =[[St<U+00E9>phane Sednaoui]] & [[Shirley Manson]]|date = 2005|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QGj6lSfk6Qw|location= ''[[Director's Label]]: The Work of Director St<U+00E9>phane Sednaoui'' | accessdate = 2006-09-23|medium = DVD| publisher = PALM Pictures}}</ref>

The black and white storyline of the video saw a young male's [[First-person narrative|first person perspective]] of exiting an elevator onto a Los Angeles street and meeting Manson. She coyly entices him to follow her to her home where the men from Garbage are waiting. They detain him inside, forcing him up onto the second-level of the house, where Manson throws him to the floor, strips him of his clothing and blinds him with [[gaffer tape]]. He recovers to find Manson shaving his head, before she drags him outside by his legs. He is then seen strangely happy, and in full colour, leaving the street.<ref name=queervideo>{{cite journal|last=Atwood|first=Brett|title=Bowie Gets Graphic, Garbage Clips 'Queer'; Garbage in, Garbage out|date=1995-09-16|journal=Billboard|location=Los Angeles|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6Q0EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=RA1-PA82&dq=Garbage%20Queer&pg=RA1-PA82#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> 

[[File:Queermakingof.png|thumb|right|Director [[St<U+00E9>phane Sednaoui]] shot the whole video himself with a [[hand-held camera]]. Here singer [[Shirley Manson]] spins him.]]

Sednaoui operated the camera for the whole shoot.<ref name="Sednaoui"/> To capture the victim's struggle, Sednaoui positioned the camera at ground-level facing upwards towards Garbage, who were standing on a rotating platform. To suggest the victim was almost hallucinating, [[strobe lighting]] was combined with the rotation of the platform, however the effect caused the band to suffer from [[vertigo]] after a number of takes.<ref name=queervideo/> Manson later claimed that the video helped establish her group; "He really defined for us who we were visually. St<U+00E9>phane was able to look at the band and listen to the music and figure out what was the perfect visual partner for the band. People think we're a very stylish band, and it's all to do with him". She added, "I'm really proud of "Queer", I think it's one of our best videos."<ref name="Sednaoui"/>

The "Queer" video premiered on North American networks on August 14, 1995;<ref>{{cite web|title=Queer / Stephane Sednaoui|url=http://cocatalog.loc.gov/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?v1=6&ti=1,6&Search_Arg=Garbage%20Queer&Search_Code=FT*&CNT=100&PID=712KLENMU8ga4Oo5WObkqsf7m0f&SEQ=20110727114244&SID=2|publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]]|accessdate=2011-07-27|date=1995-08-14|quote=PA0000704796; Queer / Stephane Sednaoui; Videocassette; 3/4 in; Music video performed by Garbage; Almo Sounds}}</ref> where it was given heavy support by MTV, who certified it a [[Buzz Bin|Buzz Clip]].<ref name=Serendipitous/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Aston|first=Martin|title=New to Q; Garbage|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|location=UK|pages=23|date=October 1995}}</ref> MTV requested an edit to [[fade (filmmaking)|obscure the shot]] of Manson blinding the video's protagonist before playlisting it.<ref name=queervideo/> The music video for "Queer" was nominated in the [[MTV Video Music Award <U+2013> Breakthrough Video|Breakthrough Video]] category at the [[1996 MTV Video Music Awards]],<ref name="MTVVMAs">{{cite journal|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wgcEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA79&dq=Garbage%20Queer&pg=PA79#v=onepage&q=Garbage%20Queer&f=false |title=Pumpkins Lead Video Music Award Noms |journal=Billboard magazine|date=1996-08-12|first=Brett|last=Atwood|pages=76|accessdate=2011-01-19}}</ref> losing to [[Smashing Pumpkins]]' "[[Tonight, Tonight (The Smashing Pumpkins song)|Tonight, Tonight]]".<ref>{{cite web|title=MTV Video Music Awards {{!}} 1996|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/1996/|publisher=Viacom, MTV|accessdate=2011-07-27|quote=Among the awards they nabbed were Breakthrough Video and Video of the Year for "Tonight, Tonight,"}}</ref> The silver dress Manson wore in the video was later donated to the [[Hard Rock Hotel and Casino (Las Vegas)|Hard Rock Hotel & Casino]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] for indefinite display.<ref name="fastfacts">{{cite web | url=http://www.garbage.com/press/articles/fastfacts.html | title=Garbage Fast Facts | publisher=Garbage.com | accessdate=2007-05-21 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20001007074107/http://www.garbage.com/press/articles/fastfacts.html |archivedate = 2000-10-07 |quote=On October 6, the Hard Rock Hotel & Casino in Las Vegas, NV received a donated piece of Garbage memorabilia. The outfit Shirley Manson wore in the "Queer" video -- from the band's multi-platinum debut album -- will be on display indefinitely.}}</ref>

The "Queer" video was first commercially released, accompanied with [[out-take]] footage from the shoot, on 1996's ''[[Garbage Video]]'' [[VHS]] and [[Video-CD]].<ref name="GarbageVideo">{{cite book|title=The Screens Are Full of Garbage|publisher=[[Melody Maker]]|location=UK|date=1996-12-07}}</ref> A remastered version was included on Garbage's 2007 greatest hits DVD ''[[Absolute_Garbage#Absolute_Garbage_DVD|Absolute Garbage]]''<ref name="absolutegarbage"/> and made available as a [[Music download|digital download]] via [[Online music store|online music services]] the same year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Garbage - Queer video|url=http://itunes.apple.com/gb/music-video/queer/id261588312|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2011-07-16}}</ref>

